File: Two SAA aeroplanes seen at an airport. AFP/Michele Spatari JOHANNESBURG - The Takatso Consortium will be giving South African Airways R3-billion over the next two years. This, as it forges ahead with its acquisition of a 51 percent controlling stake in the airline. READ: SAA financial woes | Auditor-General vows money will not be 'lost' But the relaunch of SAA will continue to be a burden on taxpayers because of the business rescue obligations. These remain the responsibility of the Public Enterprises Department. READ: SAA deal still to be finalised: Public Enterprises Committee The consortium says that it has an experienced and capable team ready to run SAA as soon as all regulatory approvals are given. Those that must okay the transaction include the Competition Commission and the Civil Aviation Authority Public Enterprises will retain a 49 percent equity stake in SAA.